#### Limited Wish
*14th-level School of Transmutation feature*<br/>
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You have learned the basic principles behind the *wish* spell, allowing you to use a lessened version of it. You can spend a spell slot of 6th level or below to cast any spell one level or lower, regardless of whether it is a wizard spell or in your spellbook. You do not need to provide any material components for the spell, unless they cost more than <br/> 100 gp and are consumed by the spell.

You can use this ability a number of times equal to your proficiency bonus and regain all expended uses when you finish a long rest.

\pagebreakNum

## The Problem with Wizards
While the wizard is generally well-received, particularly in contrast to classes like the ranger which have required multiple revisions, there are a few complaints that can be heard from time to time. Aside from issues involving 

**First**, the Dungeon Master's Guide does not provide any resources on how to handle the fact that unlike other classes, a wizard can acquire additional spells--AKA, class features--in the course of an adventure. How many spell scrolls are they expected to come across? Several per level? Are they found in a shop, in random chests? How would this affect a low-magic setting?

**Second**, the extreme gold cost of acquiring these new spells. We know the basics: in order to add the 1st-level spell *identify* to their spellbook, a wizard must consume 50 gp worth of materials. But if they do not conveniently come across a scroll or spellbook containing it, they must also purchase said scroll. Using the rough guidelines for spell scroll costs in 

Xth, lack of roleplaying resources

Xth, unable to change out spells on a short rest

Xth, less prepared spells than the other full casters, clerics and druids

Xth, the savant feature


he extreme cost of acquiring new spells for a spellbook. T

A commonly heard Every wizard subclass from the Player's Handbook has a variation of the feature:

> #### Evocation Savant
> Beginning when you select this school at 2nd level, the gold and time you must spend to copy a Evocation spell into your spellbook is halved.

This leads to a weird scenario where you have a financial incentive to choose spells from schools *other* than your school of choice

Changed to

> #### Evocation Savant
> Beginning when you select this school at 2nd level, when preparing spells from your spellbook, you can prepare an additional number of spells equal to half your wizard level (rounded up). These extra spells must be from the evocation school.

You are no longer financially incentivized to 

